=================

# Problem Without Load Balance
------------------------------

=> If we deploy our application on single server,If So many Requests will come to our  our server,burden will increase on cpu so, response  delay happend and  our server will crash,so it is a single point of failure. and our application will not run.so this is not recommaned to deploy in single server.

Single Server Disadvantages
---------------------------
Single Point of Failure – Server crash stops the whole application.

High CPU Load – Too many requests overload the server.

Slow Response – Requests take longer to process under heavy load.

No Scalability – Hard to handle increasing traffic.

Downtime Risk – Maintenance or failure makes the app unavailable.

Performance Issues – Application slows down as load increases.

# Load Balancer
---------------
=> Instead of deploying our application in single server ,we will deploy our applicaiton in multiple servers that is called load balancer.

=> One Load Balancer will be available for our application,and all the servers will be register with load balancer,customer will send the request to the load balancer,then load balancer distribute the requests to all the servers which are running on our application in Round Robin Fashion.1st request will go the 1st server,2nd request will go the 2nd server,3rd request will go the 3rd server,

Load Balancer Advantages
------------------------

Traffic Distribution – Requests are spread across multiple servers.

Better Performance – Reduces load on individual servers.

High Availability – Other servers handle traffic if one fails.

Fault Tolerance – Prevents application downtime.

Easy Scalability – New servers can be added easily.

Faster Responses – Requests go to the least busy server.

Health Monitoring – Detects and removes unhealthy servers.

# Implementation Load Balancer
------------------------------

**Client Side Load Balancer**
------------------------------

=>Remove Port No from for which service we want load balancing(ex:Product Service(Producer))

=>In order verify the port is changed or not print the port no from that service controller (ex:Product Service(Producer))
Ex:
package com.productservice.controller;

import org.springframework.beans.factory.annotation.Autowired;
import org.springframework.core.env.Environment;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.GetMapping;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.RestController;


@RestController
public class ProductController {

    @Autowired
    private Environment environment;

    @GetMapping("/getProduct")
    public String getProduct() {
        return "Product Fetched Successfully!!"+"Port No -> "+"("+environment.getProperty("server.port")+")";
    }


}

=>we have to run our Service with 3 or more Different port no's(Ex:Product Service (producer))

=> Call the Producer Service service using FeignClient

=>Feign client will ask the service registry for producer how many url's avaialble ,if we run on using 3 ports we have 3 diff url's,so Feign Client dont know which url to use,so In Feign Client one Concept called **Ribbon** it will Repeat the server callings,so instead of hitting all request to same server,it will  call one by one,for first request first server ,for second request second server for that third server,then repeat.

=>In Feign Client only Ribbon will be there to maintaion Load Balancing.

=>If we want load balancer for client side must and shd we have to use Feign Client only,With Rest Template and Web Client Load Balancer will not work.

=>If want to Use Rest Template or Web Client Only we will create load balancer at **Server Side**(Ex:Consumer Side(user-service)) cloud will provide load balancer like azure or aws.

=>**Server side Load Balancing** is good when we are deploy our project in cloud(AWS,Azure)


